Data-Driven Insights into Medication Errors Across Healthcare Settings¶

S. Taylor¶

A healthcare-focused data analysis project emphasizing real-world data challenges, exploratory insight generation, and decision-oriented storytelling.

Project Introduction¶

This project analyzes real-world medication safety incident data from the National Reporting and Learning System (NRLS) in England and Wales to identify patterns in errors, reported harm, and contributing process factors across healthcare settings. Using incident-level data, the analysis examines where errors occur, which types are most common, and how they vary by workflow stage, location, and care setting. The project accounts for real-world challenges such as incomplete reporting and inconsistent categorical data, applying transparent data preparation techniques to ensure analytical rigor. Insights are intended to support patient safety, quality improvement, and risk prioritization.

Project Summary¶

This project explores real-world healthcare data to uncover patterns and variations in medication errors. It transforms raw, imperfect incident data into actionable insights through systematic cleaning, exploratory analysis, and visualization, with a focus on operational and population-level considerations.

Project Objectives¶

The objective of this project is to systematically analyze medication safety incident data to identify error patterns, evaluate clinical risk, and generate insights to guide patient safety and quality improvement.

1. Data Cleansing & Preparation¶

Preprocessed and validated the dataset by labeling all missing or blank values as 'Unknown', creating a complete and reliable foundation for downstream analysis.

2. Summary Statistics¶

Provides initial validation of incident counts, error types, medication processes, guideline involvement, and temporal coverage.

3. Medication Error Analysis Workflow¶

Covers the four main stages of analysis: Overview of Medication Error Patterns, Harm Severity Stratification, Drivers and Context of Medication Errors, and Spatial and Temporal Variation.

Data Overview¶

incident_data_df | National Patient Safety Incident Data¶

This dataset contains anonymized medication error incidents reported to the National Reporting and Learning System (NRLS) in England and Wales (20162021). Each row represents a unique incident, capturing care setting, specialty, error type, process stage, and reported harm. Free-text variables and rare identifiers are redacted for confidentiality. The data support analysis of error patterns, guideline adherence, workflow vulnerabilities, and pre/post intervention effects.

Column Name Description
incidentID Unique incident identification number
CareSettingofOccurrence Care setting in which the incident occurred
Locationlvl1 Higher-level (less detailed) location of the incident
Locationlvl2 Lower-level (more detailed) location of the incident
Guidelinecausecategory Detailed coding of deviations from expected practice; hierarchical codes indicating task step and error mode.
Three-character codes: first = task step (13), second = error mode (A or R), third = error subtype (15)
C1C3: Guideline not followed or content incorrect; D: Not guideline-related; E: Insufficient info; Not: Not a medication incident
HighLevelCause Primary coding of deviations at a higher (less detailed) level.
13: Deviation from hierarchical task analysis steps 13; 4: Incident not describing a deviation
Guidelineinvolved1 / Guidelinesinvolved2 / Guidelinesinvolved3 Primary / secondary / tertiary clinical guideline involved. Codes: BNF = British National Formulary; Medusa/IMG = NHS Injectable Medicines Guide; SPC = Summary of Product Characteristics; N/A = Not involved
DoublecheckGuidelinecausecategory Secondary coding of deviations for inter-rater reliability assessment
SpecialtyLvl1 Higher-level clinical specialty of the incident
SpecialtyLvl2 Lower-level clinical specialty of the incident
ReportedDegreeofHarm Reported patient harm.
No harm: Patient not harmed; Low: Minor harm; Moderate: Short-term harm requiring treatment; Severe: Permanent/long-term harm; Death: Death caused by the incident
MedProcess Stage of medication use process at which the incident occurred
MedErrorCategory Type of medication error associated with the incident
ApprovedNameDrug1 Generic name of first drug involved
ApprovedNameDrug2 Generic name of second drug involved
ProprietaryNameDrug2 Brand name of second drug involved
ProprietaryNameDrug1 Brand name of first drug involved
RouteDrug1 Route of administration of a drug involved
Year_of_Occurrence Calendar year in which in incident occurred
Term1 Full NRLS search term matched in a free-text variable that led to inclusion of the incident in the study
Term1_In Free-text variable in which Term1 was matched

Data Cleansing & Preparation

The goal of data cleansing is to produce a reliable and analytically consistent medication error dataset while preserving realistic reporting characteristics. Missing and blank values were explicitly labeled as 'Unknown' rather than removed, keeping the dataset complete and transparent for downstream analysis.

Key Fixes Applied¶

  • Guideline Involvement (Guidelineinvolved1) 2,451 missing entries imputed as 'Unknown'.
  • Generic Drug Names
    • ApprovedNameDrug1: 487 missing 'Unknown'
    • ApprovedNameDrug2: 5,457 missing 'Unknown'
  • Proprietary Drug Names
    • ProprietaryNameDrug1: 5,593 missing 'Unknown'
    • ProprietaryNameDrug2: 5,704 missing 'Unknown'
  • Other Columns Cleaned
    • incidentID (1), Locationlvl2 (105), Guidelinesinvolved2 (5,478), Guidelinesinvolved3 (5,693),
      DoublecheckGuidelinecausecategory (5,206), RouteDrug1 (4,122), SpecialtyLvl1 (60)
    • SpecialtyLvl2 (1,241) blanks replaced with 'Unknown'.

Outcome: After these operations, the dataset contains no missing or blank values, resulting in incident_data_clean_df a robust foundation for analyzing error patterns, contributing factors, and trends. The cleaned dataset was loaded into SQLite (IncidentData) for SQL and Python-based analysis.

incident_data_clean_df = incident_data_df.copy()

# Columns where blanks (' ') should become 'Unknown'
blank_cols = [
    'incidentID', 'Guidelinesinvolved2', 'Guidelinesinvolved3', 'DoublecheckGuidelinecausecategory',
    'ApprovedNameDrug1', 'ApprovedNameDrug2', 'ProprietaryNameDrug1', 'ProprietaryNameDrug2',
    'RouteDrug1', 'SpecialtyLvl1', 'SpecialtyLvl2', 'Locationlvl2']

# Replace literal spaces with 'Unknown'
incident_data_clean_df[blank_cols] = incident_data_clean_df[blank_cols].replace(' ', 'Unknown')

# Columns where NULL/NaN should become 'Unknown'
null_cols = [
    'Guidelineinvolved1', 'ApprovedNameDrug1', 
    'ApprovedNameDrug2', 'ProprietaryNameDrug1']

# Fill NaNs with 'Unknown'
incident_data_clean_df[null_cols] = incident_data_clean_df[null_cols].fillna('Unknown')

Summary Statistics & Initial Validation

This step provides an initial quantitative overview of the medication error dataset to validate data quality and identify major patterns. Key operational metrics are summarized to highlight the distribution of harm, error types, process stages, guideline involvement, and temporal trends. These metrics set the stage for deeper analyses of contributing factors, workflow vulnerabilities, and intervention impact.

Key Metrics:

  • ReportedDegreeofHarm: Mostly No Harm (4,368); severe/fatal events are rare.
  • MedErrorCategory: Top errors = Other, Wrong/unclear dose, Omitted medicine.
  • MedProcess: Most errors occur during Administration or Prescribing.
  • Guidelinesinvolved: Majority Unknown; local/national guidelines less frequent.
  • Year_of_Occurrence: Peaks around 2019; early years sparse.

Analytic Rationale:

  • MedErrorCategory for headline analysis: low-dimensional, operationally interpretable, allows reliable comparison across units, locations, and time.
  • Guidelinecausecategory for context: identifies process and cognitive contributors, explaining why errors occurred without complicating top-level metrics.

Summarizes the distribution of patient harm, from no harm (4,368 incidents) to death (23 incidents), providing an initial view of clinical risk.

GuidelinesinvolvedAll¶

Aggregates guideline involvement across Guidelineinvolved1, Guidelinesinvolved2, and Guidelinesinvolved3 to quantify which clinical guidelines are most frequently associated with reported incidents, supporting evaluation of guideline adherence and coverage gaps.

In [256]:
%%sql
SELECT Guideline, COUNT(*) AS IncidentCount
FROM (
    SELECT Guidelineinvolved1 AS Guideline FROM IncidentData
    UNION ALL
    SELECT Guidelinesinvolved2 FROM IncidentData
    UNION ALL
    SELECT Guidelinesinvolved3 FROM IncidentData
) AS GuidelinesinvolvedAll
GROUP BY Guideline
ORDER BY IncidentCount DESC;

Provides key temporal metrics including earliest, latest, average, median, and most frequently reported year, offering a concise overview of incident timing and central tendencies for longitudinal analysis.

In [228]:
%%sql
SELECT 
    MIN(Year_of_Occurrence) AS Earliest_Year_Recorded,
    ROUND(AVG(Year_of_Occurrence), 2) AS Avg_Year_By_Occurrence_Count,
    (
        SELECT Year_of_Occurrence
        FROM IncidentData
        GROUP BY Year_of_Occurrence
        ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC, Year_of_Occurrence ASC
        LIMIT 1
    ) AS Year_Appearing_Most,
    (
        SELECT AVG(Year_of_Occurrence)
        FROM (SELECT Year_of_Occurrence
              FROM IncidentData
              ORDER BY Year_of_Occurrence
              LIMIT 2 - (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM IncidentData) % 2
              OFFSET (SELECT (COUNT(*) - 1) / 2
                      FROM IncidentData))
    ) AS Median_Year_By_Occurrence_Count,
    MAX(Year_of_Occurrence) AS Latest_Year_Recorded
FROM IncidentData;

 * sqlite:///MEA.db
Done.
Out[228]:
Earliest_Year_Recorded Avg_Year_By_Occurrence_Count Year_Appearing_Most Median_Year_By_Occurrence_Count Latest_Year_Recorded
1951 2018.41 2019 2018.0 2021

Medication Error Analysis Workflow¶

Covers the four main stages of analysis: Overview of Medication Error Patterns, Harm Severity Stratification, Drivers and Context of Medication Errors, and Spatial and Temporal Variation.

  1. Overview of Medication Error Patterns
    • Understanding where medication errors cluster (MedErrorCategory, ApprovedNameDrug1, ApprovedNameDrug2) helps prioritize interventions and reduce patient risk.
    • Including the 10 most frequent error types shows which errors are most common, guiding attention to high-volume issues like wrong dose or omitted medicine.
    • Tracking errors by the most frequently implicated drugs identifies medications with repeated incidents, informing targeted education or process adjustments.


  1. Harm Severity Stratification
    • Breaking down errors by ReportedDegreeofHarm reveals not just how often errors occur, but how serious they are, helping teams prioritize interventions based on potential patient impact.
    • Including all harm levels shows that most errors (e.g., wrong dose, omitted medicine) are low- or no-harm, highlighting frequent, low-risk issues that still affect workflow.
    • Excluding 'No Harm' focuses attention on clinically significant errors, showing which error types (e.g., wrong dose, adverse drug reactions) contribute most to patient risk and need targeted prevention.


  1. Drivers and Context of Medication Errors
    • Analyzing Guidelinecausecategory highlights underlying process and cognitive contributors, showing which guideline-related causes drive the most incidents.
    • Contextualizing error types within guideline causes shows which combinations (e.g., wrong dose under specific guideline causes) create high-risk scenarios.
    • Evaluating MedProcess identifies stages in the medication use workflow most prone to errors, highlighting opportunities for process improvement.
    • Mapping errors to GuidelinesinvolvedAll clarifies which clinical guidelines are most frequently implicated, helping prioritize guideline review or staff training.


  1. Spatial and Temporal Variation
    • Examining error trends over time (Year_of_Occurrence) identifies periods of increased incidents and sustained problem areas, guiding time-based interventions.
    • Stratifying by harm level over time shows that high-severity events remain consistent, informing risk-based safety strategies.
    • Tracking errors by category over time identifies persistent problem areas, signaling where sustained attention is needed.
    • Comparing error distributions across CareSettingofOccurrence, Locationlvl1, and Locationlvl2 highlights hotspots in hospitals, inpatient areas, and other care settings, guiding spatial targeting of interventions.

1. Overview of Medication Error Patterns¶

Understanding where medication errors cluster helps prioritize interventions and reduce patient risk.

Understanding where medication errors cluster by MedErrorCategory, ApprovedNameDrug1, and ApprovedNameDrug2 highlights which error types and medications drive the most incidents, so teams can target improvements and reduce patient risk.

  • Dose, strength, and omission errors drive the highest incident counts, showing where processes need the most attention.
  • Specific medications are repeatedly involved in errors, highlighting high-risk drugs for monitoring and staff focus.
  • Many errors involve unidentified drugs, signaling gaps in documentation that could compromise patient safety.

df_harm_all = pd.read_sql("""

    MedErrorCategory,
    COUNT(*) AS IncidentCount

GROUP BY ReportedDegreeofHarm, MedErrorCategory

df_harm = pd.read_sql("""
SELECT 
    ReportedDegreeofHarm,
    MedErrorCategory,
    COUNT(*) AS IncidentCount
FROM IncidentData
GROUP BY ReportedDegreeofHarm, MedErrorCategory
HAVING ReportedDegreeofHarm != 'No Harm'
ORDER BY IncidentCount DESC;
""", con)

df_harm_pivot = df_harm.pivot_table(
    index='ReportedDegreeofHarm',
    columns='MedErrorCategory',
    values='IncidentCount',
    fill_value=0
)

colors_list_harm = colors[:len(df_harm_pivot.columns)]

df_harm_all_pivot = df_harm_all.pivot_table(
    index='ReportedDegreeofHarm',
    columns='MedErrorCategory',
    values='IncidentCount',
    fill_value=0

# --- Create vertical subplots ---

3. Drivers and Context of Medication Errors¶

Analyzing medication errors by Guidelinecausecategory, MedErrorCategory, MedProcess, and GuidelinesinvolvedAll reveals the underlying drivers and context of errors, helping teams prioritize interventions based on systemic risk and workflow vulnerabilities.

  • Most errors are linked to a few guideline cause categories, with the top two accounting for nearly half of incidents, highlighting systemic areas that need review.
  • Within these categories, wrong doses and omitted medicines dominate, showing the specific errors to address through training or process changes.
  • Administration and prescribing stages account for the highest number of errors, pinpointing stages where interventions will have the largest effect.
  • The majority of guideline-related errors occur with local or frequently used guidelines, indicating opportunities for standardization and reinforcement.

guide_errors = pd.read_sql("""
WITH GuidelinesCombined AS (
    SELECT Guidelineinvolved1 AS Guideline FROM IncidentData
    UNION ALL
    SELECT Guidelinesinvolved2 FROM IncidentData
    UNION ALL
    SELECT Guidelinesinvolved3 FROM IncidentData
)
SELECT 
    Guideline AS GuidelinesinvolvedAll,
    COUNT(*) AS IncidentCount
FROM GuidelinesCombined
GROUP BY Guideline
HAVING GuidelinesinvolvedAll != 'Unknown'
ORDER BY IncidentCount DESC;
""", con)

4. Spatial and Temporal Variation¶

Examining medication errors over time (Year_of_Occurrence) and across locations (CareSettingofOccurrence, Locationlvl1, Locationlvl2) highlights trends and hotspots, helping teams target interventions where and when errors are most likely to occur.

  • Overall incidents have increased sharply since 2014, with peaks around 20182019, showing periods where workload or system changes may have contributed to errors.
  • Stratifying by harm level shows that high-severity events remain relatively low, but still occur consistently each year, guiding risk-based safety efforts.
  • Tracking errors by category over time identifies persistent problem areas, like wrong dose and omitted medicines, signaling areas for sustained attention.
  • Errors are concentrated in acute/general hospitals and inpatient areas, indicating that these settings are high-priority targets for process improvements.
  • Community, primary care, and outpatient settings account for smaller but significant numbers of incidents, showing that interventions should extend beyond hospitals.

Conclusion¶

This analysis of medication safety incidents delivers a detailed understanding of error patterns, contributing factors, and workflow vulnerabilities across healthcare settings. By examining error types, harm severity, process stages, guideline involvement, and spatialtemporal trends, the report generates actionable insights for patient safety and quality improvement.

Key Takeaways:

  • Medication errors are most frequently associated with wrong/unclear dose, omitted medicines, and other administration errors, highlighting areas requiring process-focused interventions.
  • Most incidents result in no or low harm, but moderate to severe events still occur, emphasizing the need for risk-targeted safety measures.
  • Errors cluster in Administration and Prescribing stages, revealing workflow vulnerabilities and opportunities for process redesign and staff training.
  • Guideline-related contributors show that local and frequently used clinical guidelines are implicated in the majority of incidents, pointing to standardization and adherence improvement opportunities.
  • Spatial analysis shows acute/general hospitals and inpatient areas as hotspots, while community and primary care settings, though lower in volume, still require attention.
  • Temporal trends reveal a peak in incidents around 20182019, suggesting systemic pressures or reporting changes, with high-harm events remaining relatively stable.

Overall, these insights equip patient safety teams, clinical managers, and healthcare analysts to monitor risk, target interventions, and optimize workflows to reduce medication errors and improve care quality.

Future Recommendations:

  • Focus training, process redesign, and double-check protocols on high-risk stages, particularly Administration and Prescribing.
  • Target interventions for high-risk medications repeatedly involved in incidents.
  • Standardize and reinforce clinical guideline adherence, especially for local and widely used guidelines.
  • Implement spatially focused safety strategies in hospitals and inpatient units while maintaining coverage in outpatient and community care.
  • Track trends over time to assess intervention effectiveness and anticipate periods of increased risk.
  • Maintain ongoing data quality and completeness efforts to ensure reliable incident reporting and monitoring.
